                <head>178. Memorandum From Secretary of Defense Brown to the President’s Assistant
                    for National Security Affairs (Brzezinski)<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d178fn1">Source: Carter Library, National Security Affairs,
                        Brzezinski Material, Brzezinski Office File, Subject Chron File, Box 89,
                            Doctrine/<gloss target="#t_C3I_1">C<hi rend="superscript"
                            >3</hi>I</gloss>: 1979–1980. Secret; Restricted Data.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1980-03-07">March 7, 1980</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Contingency Plans for Increased Strategic Capability (<gloss
                            target="#t_U_1">U</gloss>)</item>
                </list>
                <p>(<gloss target="#t_S_1">S</gloss>) Last year’s <gloss target="#t_NIE_1"
                        >NIE</gloss> raised the prospect that the Soviets could pull ahead of us in
                    warheads in the early 1980’s.<note n="2" xml:id="d178fn2">See <ref
                            target="#d111">Document 111</ref>.</note> That conclusion was partly
                    because of inconsistent rules for counting U.S. and Soviet <gloss
                        target="#t_SSBN_1">SSBN</gloss>s on sea trials. Furthermore, in the event
                    Soviet deployments of highly fractionated <gloss target="#t_SLBM_1"
                    >SLBM</gloss>s and <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">ICBM</gloss>s have progressed more
                    slowly than the <gloss target="#t_NIE_1">NIE</gloss> predicted, [<hi
                        rend="italic">1 line not declassified</hi>] It now appears unlikely that we
                    will lose our lead in warheads in the early 1980’s. Nonetheless, I share your
                    belief that we must be prepared to take further actions. If <gloss
                        target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> II collapses, our planned forces may be
                    inadequate, particularly in the mid-1980’s before MX can be deployed in
                    numbers.</p>
                <pb facs="0794" n="769" xml:id="pg_769"/>
                <p>(<gloss target="#t_S_1">S</gloss>) My staff has examined a number of options, as
                    illustrated by the attached table. The shortest and cheapest path to a real
                    increase in our strategic and theater nuclear capabilities would be to
                    accelerate deployment of cruise missiles—<gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">ALCM</gloss>,
                        <gloss target="#t_GLCM_1">GLCM</gloss>, and perhaps <gloss
                        target="#t_SLCM_1">SLCM</gloss>. [<hi rend="italic">2 lines not
                        declassified</hi>] We have also examined the option of converting POLARIS
                    submarines to <gloss target="#t_SLCM_1">SLCM</gloss> launchers with 80 or more
                    per boat. It is not necessary to choose among <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1"
                        >ALCM</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_GLCM_1">GLCM</gloss>, or <gloss
                        target="#t_SLCM_1">SLCM</gloss> now, however, in part because these missiles
                    share so many components. My staff is examining actions we can take to cut the
                    lead time for increasing production; I will let you know our plans in the near
                    future.</p>
                <p>(SRD) One other problem that could limit our response to a breakdown in <gloss
                        target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> is the supply of special nuclear material.
                    According to the “Moderate No-<gloss target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss>” estimate
                    in Draft <gloss target="#t_NIE_1">NIE</gloss> 11–3/8–79 the Soviets could deploy
                    an additional 8000 warheads by 1989.<note n="3" xml:id="d178fn3">For the final
                        version, see the attachment to <ref target="#d184">Document
                        184</ref>.</note> [<hi rend="italic">6 lines not declassified</hi>]
                    Therefore, if we want to prepare for this contingency, we should soon increase
                    production of special nuclear material.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BH_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Harold Brown</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
